Introduction

SECHSKIES (formerly stylized as Sechs Kies) is a South Korean boy group currently consisting of four members: Eun Jiwon, Lee Jaijin, Kim Jaeduck, and Jang Suwon. The group originally had two unofficial sub-units: Black Kies (Eun Jiwon, Lee Jaijin, Kim Jaeduck) and White Kies (Kang Sunghoon, Ko Jiyong, Jang Suwon).

The group debuted on April 15, 1997, with their studio album School Byeolgok under Daesung Entertainment, now known as DSP Media. On January 12, 2000, they celebrated their 1000th day with fans but abruptly announced their disbandment at a press conference on May 18, 2000. The sudden breakup at the height of their career fueled rumors, including speculation of forced disbandment by DSP, though members have given differing accounts over the years.

After the disbandment, all members except Ko Jiyong remained in the entertainment industry. Eun Jiwon, Kang Sunghoon, and Lee Jaijin pursued solo careers and television appearances, while Kim Jaeduck and Jang Suwon formed the duo J-WALK and continued promotions until their military service.

On April 4, 2016, SECHSKIES reunited for a concert with five members: Eun Jiwon, Kang Sunghoon, Lee Jaijin, Kim Jaeduck, and Jang Suwon. Ko Jiyong did not participate, having left the entertainment industry after the disbandment. On May 11, 2016, YG Entertainment announced the group had signed a contract with the agency, along with exclusive contracts for Kang Sunghoon and Lee Jaijin. By 2017, the other members also signed with YG Entertainment.

On September 21, 2018, YG announced that Kang Sunghoon would temporarily step back from SECHSKIES activities due to ongoing scandals, and the release of their next album was delayed. On December 31, 2018, YG confirmed that Kang Sunghoon had officially left the group, and his contract with the company was terminated.

As of 2024, SECHSKIES' profile has been removed from YG Entertainment's website.
